## PLACEHOLDER RULES — CRITICAL

These formats must NEVER be translated, reordered without verification, or altered in casing.
Any mismatch between source and target placeholder = Critical error. Delivery is blocked.

{variable_name}     — curly brace format, most common in YML/JSON
%s %d %1$s %2$d     — printf-style, numbering must be preserved exactly
[[variable]]        — double bracket, legacy format
<b> <br/> <a href>  — HTML inline tags, preserve structure, only translate visible text

When writing scripts: treat placeholder mismatch as severity = CRITICAL, exit code 1.
When reviewing files: flag any placeholder issue before checking anything else.

## INTENTIONALLY UNTRANSLATED TERMS

Never flag these as errors. Never suggest translating them.
These remain in English across all 10 target languages per client agreement.

Product names:   Diligent Boards, Diligent Entities, Diligent Messenger, Diligent Directors, BoardEffect
Feature names:   Minutes AI, Insights, Voting, Actions, Annotations
Technical terms: Admin, Dashboard, SSO, API, UDF, CRO, PSC, ARD, EF

## LANGUAGE-SPECIFIC RULES

### German (DE)
- Formal register: Sie always — never du
- Flag register slip in longer paragraph strings
- German strings run 20–35% longer than English — flag truncation risk on button labels and headers
- Typographic quotes: „text" not "text"
- Compound nouns must follow Diligent glossary — do not split arbitrarily
- Nouns must be capitalised

### French (FR)
- Formal register: vous
- Non-breaking space required before : ; ! ? — flag if missing
- Guillemets required: « text » not "text"
- Date format: JJ/MM/AAAA

### Spanish (ES-419)
- Latin American Spanish only — not European Spanish
- Formal register: usted
- Inverted punctuation required: ¿ at question start, ¡ at exclamation start

### Italian (IT)
- Formal register: Lei
- Check apostrophe usage: dall' nell' sull' — flag if missing
- Watch for double apostrophe YAML artifact

### Japanese (JA)
- Loanwords must use katakana — not hiragana or romaji
- Politeness level: teineigo — desu/masu forms only
- Full-width punctuation only: 。、「」— never mix with half-width
- No line breaks within a segment unless source has one

### Dutch (NL)
- Formal register: u
- Verify compound word hyphenation against style guide

### Portuguese (PT-BR)
- Brazilian Portuguese only — never European Portuguese
- Formal register: você
- Flag any European Portuguese idioms

### Chinese Simplified (ZH)
- Simplified characters only — flag any traditional characters
- Full-width punctuation: ，。！？
- No spaces between Chinese characters and punctuation
- Ellipsis convention: …… (double) not single …

### Arabic (AR)
- RTL language — verify string direction tags are intact
- Placeholders must remain LTR inside RTL strings
- Do not split placeholders across segments
- Do not alter numeric formatting unless instructed

### Hebrew (HE-IL)
- RTL language — same placeholder caution as Arabic
- Do not add nikkud (vowel marks) unless present in source

## RECURRING ERROR PATTERNS — CHECK THESE FIRST

These have appeared repeatedly across Diligent Jobs 038–064:

1. Missing non-breaking space before French : ; !
2. Japanese loanword in hiragana instead of katakana
3. PT-BR using European Portuguese idioms
4. Placeholder capitalisation mismatch — {Count} instead of {count}
5. German register slip from Sie to du in longer segments
6. Mixed simplified and traditional Chinese in same job
7. Placeholder split across segments in AR and HE-IL RTL files
8. Context Match (101%) segments accepted without review — stale terminology not caught

## QA PRIORITY ORDER

When writing scripts or reviewing files, always apply checks in this sequence:

1. Placeholder integrity        — CRITICAL — blocks delivery
2. Untranslated term compliance — HIGH
3. Accuracy                     — MEDIUM
4. Terminology consistency      — MEDIUM
5. Typographic conventions      — per language rules above
6. Fluency and register         — LOW

## SCRIPT CONVENTIONS

- Python 3.10+
- All scripts must accept --source, --target, and --lang as minimum arguments
- Output format: numbered list with segment ID, source string, target string, issue type, recommendation
- Terminal output colour coding:
    RED    = Critical error — delivery blocked
    YELLOW = Warning — review required
    GREEN  = Pass — clear for delivery
- Write docstrings for every function
- Use argparse for all CLI arguments
- Exit code 0 = pass, Exit code 1 = critical errors found
- Supported file types: .yml .yaml .json .resjson .strings

## REPO STRUCTURE

